Over the course of these 25 years, Putin has transformed his country into the "strong custom dictatorship of the world", said Russian polythologist Mikhail Komin>. He did this because he gradually and constantly undermined all Russian political institutions and also became the archetype for a new model of world politics as the Financial Times journalist Gideon Rachman wrote in his book 'The Age of The Strongman'> (2022). Rachman, not by chance, began the "strong man age" on 31 December 1999: Putin was inspired by a generation of authoritarian leaders who admire its nationalism, aggressive rhetoric, conservatism, contempt of "politically correct", its focus on people's rights and not the individual in polemic with liberal democracies.
